        "Noelle is back at her workstation chair."

        "She is typing."

        "The keystrokes are faster than they were before Aeron arrived. Not because she is in a drafting register -- she is not. The new model document is still mostly blank. The cursor has moved from the first line to approximately the middle of the third line. The typing is not the cursor's progress on the model. The typing is Noelle setting up the model's structural parameters in a different document window."

        "The structural parameters are things like: what is the new frame's unit of measurement. What is the new frame's primary axis. What is the new frame's relationship to the analyst-frame's concept of distributional trust."

        "The structural parameters are the scaffolding for a model she has not yet written. The scaffolding comes before the sentences."

        "Aeron is beside the workstation. He is standing, not sitting. His left hand is flat on the bezel of the primary screen -- the same position as a4_s10. The hand is there because the hand goes there. The hand is not tremoring."

        "Noelle does not look at the hand."

        "She does not look at Aeron."

        "She is looking at the scaffolding document. Her fingers are building the scaffolding at the speed they build things when they are building in a register that has not been named yet."

        # --- NOELLE'S INTERIOR ---

        nthought "The old frame would have required me to stop and document the last hour."

        nthought "The old frame required documentation of everything. Documentation was the old frame's relationship to keeping."

        nthought "I am not documenting the last hour."

        nthought "I am not documenting the last hour because the last hour is not a dataset. The last hour is a condition change. The condition change does not produce a log entry. The condition change produces a new scaffolding."

        nthought "The scaffolding is what I am writing right now."

        nthought "The scaffolding is the new frame's method of keeping. The new frame keeps by structure, not by log."

        nthought "I am not going to look at him while I write the scaffolding."

        nthought "I am not going to look at him because looking at him is a thing the old frame would have predicted -- the analyst looking at her subject for behavioral variance data. The old frame is the frame I am replacing. Not looking at him is the first act of the new frame."

        nthought "He is standing at the screen with his hand on the bezel. The hand is still there. The hand was the input. The hand is now back to being a hand at the bezel. The position is the position I have been cataloguing for three months."

        nthought "The cataloguing is the old frame."

        nthought "I notice I am still cataloguing."

        nthought "The cataloguing is going to persist longer than the analyst frame because the cataloguing is a habit layer below the frame. The habit layer does not go away because the frame above it has been replaced. The habit layer persists."

        nthought "I am going to let the habit layer persist and build the new frame on top of it."

        nthought "The new frame is going to be built on top of a habit layer that still catalogues his hand."

        nthought "The new frame is going to ignore the cataloguing even though the cataloguing is still happening."

        nthought "The ignoring is the frame's first operation."

        nthought "I am ignoring it now."

        nthought "The scaffolding is getting built."

